{With 9 points you have just enough to respond. And with a 4-card Major suit you should use Stayman so you bid 2\C. Partner duly replies 2\S.  

With 9 points you have just enough to respond. And with a 4-card Major suit you should use Stayman so you bid 2\C. Partner duly replies 2\S. 

You don't have a 4-4 \H fit, so you invite the notrump game by bidding 2NT. Partner raises to 3NT.

The contract would be 3NT played by North.

South plays 3NT and West leads the \DQ. Should you win or hold up?

A pretty good argument against holding up could be that they might switch to \Ss. However, say you do in fact hold up and that West does in fact continue \Ds with East following suit.

Winner List: \S = 2 : \H = 0 : \D = 2 : \C = 4 :: Total = 8

Don't worry any more about the \Ds since there is nothing more you can do. Instead, worry about where that one more winner is going to come from. The answer will have to be: <i>from the \H suit</i>. 

You might be tempted to take your 4 \C tricks right away, but avoid the temptation. The \C suit is your convenient transportation back and forth between hands.

You will have to lose at least 2 \H tricks in order to set up 1 winner, and by the time you do that the defenders will have established at least 1 more \D trick. What that means is that you cannot afford 3 \H losers. So how will you play the \Hs? 

You should play West for the \HJ plus one of the big ones. This is a better chance than playing him for both the \H A K. So play a \H toward dummy and insert the \H10 when West plays low. East wins with the \HA and clears the \Ds. Play another \H toward dummy's \HQ. West can take his \HK and cash his \D winner but dummy's \HQ will be your ninth trick.

There were two \H distributions which would allow you to make this contract.

West could hold both the \HA and \HK, in which case leading toward dummy's \HQ would be the winning play.

West could hold <b>EITHER</b> \H A J x <b>OR</b>\H K J x in which case finessing dummy's \HJ would be the winning play. This is the more likely distribution of the two.}
[Play "W"]DQ

