[Student "S"]
{You should not make a takeout double with three cards in their suit. A 2\D overcall would be a reasonable choice. But with 15 points, balanced, and a stopper in \Hs a 1NT overcall is probably better.

Partner bids 3NT.

South plays 3NT. As expected, West leads his partner's \H suit.

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 1/2 : \D = 0 : \C = 3 :: Total = 5/6

You need at least 4 \D winners.

If you play low from dummy on the \H lead East can win the \HK but this will give you an extra \H stopper. He could drive out dummy's \HA at trick 2, but you would then establish \Ds and make an overtrick! 

But who said East would play another \H after winning the \HK? What if he wins the \HK and switches to \Ss? They might then win 3 \S tricks to go with their \HK and \DA. 

Instead you should grab the first trick with dummy's \HA and start playing \Ds. East will take the \DA but you still have the \SA and \HQ as stoppers.

Just look at East's hand. If you duck the \HA it will be crystal clear to him that he can defeat the contract by winning the \HK and then switching to the \SK.

Don't give him the chance.}
[Play "W"]H8

